54723,"guid":"AF03F61371AC46489A7C550140D52D01","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Basic Navigation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"5417DAA052994869BE5592DFD7BAD905","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Get me out of here!<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">This will change your location to the path specified after the cd command. The path can be either absolute or relative. To explain the difference look at the example file tree shown below.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/public\/01a7878d3c622e9c4d27343721a1b5c5559e4cb768b63015146659aa9ec62085\/cnk4bgvt7.png\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>An <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">absolute<\/span><span> path always starts from the root directory which in UNIX is represented by a \/<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Therefore the absolute path to the data directory of user1 is<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">\/home\/user1\/data<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">The absolute path to the bin directory is <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">\/usr\/bin<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Therefore to change directories to these place <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">no matter where you are <\/span><span>youcan type<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">cd \/home\/user1\/data<\/span><span> or <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">cd \/usr\/bin <\/span><span>respectively.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>A <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">relative<\/span><span>path is a location starting from the current working directory and does <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">not <\/span><span>start with a \/.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">If you need to go back up a directory you type .. which stands for up a level into the parent directory. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Therefore if you are in the directory \/home\/user1<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">to navigate to the data directory you would type <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span>    <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">cd data<\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">to navigate to user2 directory you would type <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span>    <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">cd ..\/user2<\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">    This navigates up a level in the tree to home and then down into user2<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">If your present working directory is \/usr\/bin to navigate to the user 1 documents directory you could<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">use the absolute path<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span>    <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">cd \/home\/user1\/documents<\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Use the relative path<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li styl